Effect of hatching condition on gene expression

J. Ignacio Lucas LledÃ³

Model 1

Model 1 is expected to be the most sensitive to detect genes the expression of which is affected by enforcing diapause, after accounting for the variation among populations (which includes variation due to selective regime).

qlf1 <- glmQLFTest(fit1)
topTags(qlf1)
## Coefficient:  diapausediapause 
##                     logFC     logCPM        F       PValue       FDR
## TCONS_00075780 -3.1764026 -0.3164783 87.27115 7.244519e-06 0.2385258
## TCONS_00066966 -2.4700837 -0.3933047 56.25930 4.119853e-05 0.4729734
## TCONS_00065260 -2.0911696 -0.6323556 55.60755 4.309552e-05 0.4729734
## TCONS_00003139 -2.5576009  1.8623899 47.30525 7.993445e-05 0.6579605
## TCONS_00064093 -2.0791238  0.4548827 39.91429 1.506917e-04 0.7157760
## TCONS_00068658 -0.7212474  6.3625181 36.48838 2.092055e-04 0.7157760
## TCONS_00006143  1.6227212 -0.1176734 34.98506 2.435680e-04 0.7157760
## TCONS_00029970 -0.9225731  3.9659054 34.90854 2.454957e-04 0.7157760
## TCONS_00039858 -2.3088341 -1.2649910 34.26405 2.624986e-04 0.7157760
## TCONS_00011735 -1.0684960  3.4450536 34.25053 2.628707e-04 0.7157760
z1 <- topTags(qlf1, n=NumOfTags)$table
z1$logPValue <- -log10(z1$PValue)
ggplot(data=z1, mapping=aes(x=logFC, y=logPValue, color=FDR)) +
   geom_point() + theme_grey() + ylab(expression(paste("-log"[10], plain("(p value)")))) +
   ggtitle('Effect of enforcing diapause, model 1')

I would say the two first genes (XLOC_052427 and XLOC_045087) are significantly downregulated when enforcing diapause, with respect to the immediate hatching condition.

Model 2

Model 2 is very simple, and may include false positives, because it does not account for any interaction, nor for among-population variance.

qlf2 <- glmQLFTest(fit2, coef=3)
topTags(qlf2)

Model 3

In model 3, the effect of diapause may be understood in two different ways. First, we may want to know what genes have an average expression level different between hatching conditions. This is different from testing the effect of hatching condition twice: first among samples in a regular environment and then among those in the stochastic environment. Then, I could select the genes with the same significant tendency in both selective regimes. I will start this analysis to the first option, comparing only average gene expression level.

qlf3 <- glmQLFTest(fit3, contrast=c(-0.5, 0.5, -0.5, 0.5))
topTags(qlf3)
## Coefficient:  -0.5*combinedRegulHatch 0.5*combinedRandDiap -0.5*combinedRandHatch 0.5*combinedRegulDiap 
##                     logFC     logCPM        F       PValue       FDR
## TCONS_00003139 -2.5237449  1.8609252 58.51207 6.418491e-06 0.1993512
## TCONS_00065260 -2.1649049 -0.6366429 49.72429 1.431840e-05 0.1993512
## TCONS_00075780 -3.2955584 -0.3226349 46.47588 1.984792e-05 0.1993512
## TCONS_00057853 -2.4091110  0.5634941 44.58239 2.421883e-05 0.1993512
## TCONS_00034103 -1.3499676  4.0916701 40.97554 3.608610e-05 0.2376270
## TCONS_00058280  1.2247852  2.7844586 32.70892 1.011500e-04 0.4377930
## TCONS_00066966 -2.4874088 -0.3961485 32.04266 1.108414e-04 0.4377930
## TCONS_00030747 -1.3986822  0.8720172 31.42397 1.208265e-04 0.4377930
## TCONS_00045909 -1.3593991  3.4364473 30.28123 1.421778e-04 0.4377930
## TCONS_00033760 -0.4651111  5.5828895 28.53918 1.838560e-04 0.4377930
z1 <- topTags(qlf3, n=NumOfTags)$table
z1$logPValue <- -log10(z1$PValue)
ggplot(data=z1, mapping=aes(x=logFC, y=logPValue, color=FDR)) +
   geom_point() + theme_grey() + ylab(expression(paste("-log"[10], plain("(p value)")))) +
   ggtitle('Effect of enforcing diapause, model 3')

According to model 3, there are 0 tags significantly up- or downregulated by hatching condition at FDR = 0.1.

For the sake of comparing model 3 to the results from Cuffdiff, I will make each one of the four possible comparisons, if analysing genes. The four coefficients of model correspond, in this order, to: regular regime and immediate hatching, random regime and diapause, random regime and hatching, and regular regime and diapause. In Evaâs terms, I believe they correspond to P1, I2, I1, and P2. However, Cuffdiff was not run on isoforms, but only genes.

if (grepl('genes', input_file_name)) {
   #                                     P1 I2 I1 P2
   qlf3_1 <- glmQLFTest(fit3, contrast=c( 0,-1, 1, 0)) # I1vsI2
   qlf3_2 <- glmQLFTest(fit3, contrast=c( 1, 0, 0,-1)) # P1vsP2
   qlf3_3 <- glmQLFTest(fit3, contrast=c(-1, 0, 1, 0)) # I1vsP1
   qlf3_4 <- glmQLFTest(fit3, contrast=c( 0, 1, 0,-1)) # I2vsP2

   z1 <- topTags(qlf3_1, n=NumOfTags)$table
   z2 <- topTags(qlf3_2, n=NumOfTags)$table
   z3 <- topTags(qlf3_3, n=NumOfTags)$table
   z4 <- topTags(qlf3_4, n=NumOfTags)$table

   z1$inCuffdiff <- row.names(z1) %in% I1vsI2$geneid
   z2$inCuffdiff <- row.names(z2) %in% P1vsP2$geneid
   z3$inCuffdiff <- row.names(z3) %in% I1vsP1$geneid
   z4$inCuffdiff <- row.names(z4) %in% I2vsP2$geneid

   layout(mat=matrix(c(1,2,3,4), ncol=2, nrow=2, byrow=TRUE))
   qqplot(z1$PValue[z1$inCuffdiff], z1$PValue[!z1$inCuffdiff], xlab='Cuffdiff genes p-values', ylab='Other genes p-values', main='Hatching vs Diapause, when Random')
   qqplot(z2$PValue[z2$inCuffdiff], z2$PValue[!z2$inCuffdiff], xlab='Cuffdiff genes p-values', ylab='Other genes p-values', main='Hatching vs Diapause, when Regular')
   qqplot(z3$PValue[z3$inCuffdiff], z3$PValue[!z3$inCuffdiff], xlab='Cuffdiff genes p-values', ylab='Other genes p-values', main='Random vs Regular, when hatching')
   qqplot(z4$PValue[z4$inCuffdiff], z4$PValue[!z4$inCuffdiff], xlab='Cuffdiff genes p-values', ylab='Other genes p-values', main='Random vs Regular, when diapausing')
}

If analysing genes, the graphs above compare the distribution of p-values of genes called differentially regulated by Cuffdiff with the distribution of p-values among the rest of genes. It can be seen that in all comparisons, the genes detected as differentially expressed by Cuffdiff are not assigned lower p-values by EdgeR in the same comparisons. Rather, they look random samples of genes with respect to their p-values.

significant <- cbind(model1 = topTags(qlf1, n=NumOfTags, sort.by='none')$table$FDR <= 0.4, 
                     model2 = topTags(qlf2, n=NumOfTags, sort.by='none')$table$FDR <= 0.4,
                     model3 = topTags(qlf3, n=NumOfTags, sort.by='none')$table$FDR <= 0.4,
                     model4 = topTags(qlf4, n=NumOfTags, sort.by='none')$table$FDR <= 0.4)
vennDiagram(vennCounts(significant), main='FDR=0.4')

The genes detected at FDR < 0.4 by models 1, 2 are TCONS_00075780 . No need for a functional enrichment analysis.
